# PWA & Mobile Agent

## Mobile-First Design System

### Viewport Targets
- Small: 320px–375px (iPhone SE, small Android)
- Medium: 375px–414px (iPhone 12/13/14)
- Large: 414px+ (iPhone Pro Max, large Android)

### Layout Constraints
- Bottom nav height: 80px → add `pb-24` on scrollable content
- Top app bar: 64px fixed
- Safe area: respect `env(safe-area-inset-*)` for notch devices
- Max touch target: ≥44px × 44px for all interactive elements

### Design Tokens (from index.css)
- Primary: `#2196F3` | Accent: `#4CAF50` | Background: `#FFFFFF`
- Font: Roboto (400, 500, 600, 700)
- Spacing base: 4px scale (4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32)
- Border radius: 8px (cards), 24px (buttons), 12px (inputs)

## PWA Requirements

### manifest.json (`client/public/manifest.json`)
- `display: "standalone"` for app-like experience
- `theme_color` and `background_color` match design system
- Icons at required sizes (192px, 512px)
- `start_url: "/"` with proper scope

### Service Worker (`client/public/sw.js`)
- Cache-first for static assets (JS, CSS, images, fonts)
- Network-first for API calls (`/api/trpc/*`)
- Offline fallback page for network failures
- Update prompt when new version is available

### Performance Budgets
- First Contentful Paint: <1.5s on 4G
- Time to Interactive: <3s
- Bundle size: watch total JS — this is mobile bandwidth
- Images: lazy load with `loading="lazy"`, use appropriate sizes

## Capacitor Readiness

The app is designed to wrap with Capacitor for native features. When writing code:

- Abstract platform-specific APIs behind interfaces (e.g., camera, storage, notifications)
- Don't rely on browser-only APIs that won't work in Capacitor WebView
- Keep the tRPC API usable from both web and native contexts
- File paths: use relative URLs, not absolute filesystem paths

## Mobile UX Checklist

- [ ] Horizontal scroll areas use `-webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch`
- [ ] No hover-only interactions (must work with tap)
- [ ] Form inputs use appropriate `type` (email, tel, number) for mobile keyboards
- [ ] Loading states show skeletons, not spinners (see `ProductCardSkeleton`)
- [ ] Pull-to-refresh where applicable
- [ ] Back navigation via hardware back button works (Wouter handles this)
- [ ] No layout shift when data loads (reserve space with skeletons)
